annotations:
I wanna do right by you
 I wanna tend to your wounds
 I am interested
 In a love that soothes
 ‘Cause I’ve been through some rounds before

they’ve been done wrong, and been through “some rounds” in past relationships and connections,
which is most likely why they wish this current connection to be soothing for one another.
I want it to be different with you

They are hoping that loving this person will be different that their more painful “rounds” of love before, hence why they are being so adamant about making space for them when they are gone and attempting to bring this person about.

My eyes, these eyes, these days
 I got for you
 And even if I don’t get to see you
 I’m envisioning all kinds of things
Everything the narrator “sees” these days seems to be centered around this person, and even in their absence, the narrator seems to be imagining their presence anyway.

This spot, this spot
 It’s all for you
 And even if you don’t come tonight
 It’s still for you

The narrator is “saving a spot” for someone, literally or metaphorically. They would be saving a place for this person in their heart and mind, or a spot for them next to them (in bed, etc.), regardless of whether or not this person comes back to them.

description.plain:
On her debut album Lake Tear of the Clouds, Los Angeles-based singer/songwriter Cornelia Murr taps into the bucolic spirit of the Hudson Valley in upper New York State. Working with producer Jim James of My Morning Jacket, Murr conjures a hazy blend of folk and cosmic soul music, her voice floating over ghostly soundscapes that bring to mind the fantasias of Broadcast, Stereolab’s most pastoral moments, and the spooky romance of Beach House.

Murr was born in London and resides in California as a dual citizen, but spent much of her childhood moving through the United States, from Colorado to Massachusetts, California to New York City and upstate New York. It’s the latter locale that most informs the spiritual geography of the album, which invokes the cyclical journey of water from the highest point in the Adirondack Mountains to the valley below and out to sea. Like that water, Murr’s voice flows with a liquid grace.
